      passage: `The Language of Neutrality

In journalism and academic writing, the passive voice is not merely a grammatical choice — it is a rhetorical strategy. When a journalist writes "three officials are alleged to have received payments", the construction does two things simultaneously: it conveys information while withholding certainty. The writer is not asserting that the payments were received. They are reporting that the allegation exists.

This matters enormously in contexts where legal liability, factual uncertainty, or political sensitivity are in play. Consider the difference between "The CEO lied" and "The CEO is alleged to have misled investors". The first is a direct assertion that could expose a publication to defamation. The second reports a claim while embedding a hedge: "alleged" signals that the statement has not been established as fact.

The passive is equally valued in academic writing. "It has been established that..." carries more authority than "I believe that..." because it depersonalises the claim, suggesting that the finding exists independently of any individual's opinion. "The data suggest..." distances the researcher from the conclusion, implying that the evidence points in a particular direction without the writer having imposed an interpretation.

Critics of this style argue that it can be used to obscure responsibility — particularly in institutional communications. "Mistakes were made" is the classic example: a sentence in which the passive entirely removes the agent. Who made the mistakes? The passive does not say.

Understanding this structure, therefore, means more than knowing how to construct it grammatically. It means recognising when it is being used to inform, and when it is being used to evade.`,
